# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-aboriginal-languages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] The **2021 Australian census**, simply called the **2021 Census**, was the eighteenth national Census of Population and Housing in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] The 2021 Census took place on 10 August 2021, and was conducted by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] It had a response rate of 96.1%, up from the 95.1% at the 2016 census.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] The total population of the Commonwealth of Australia was counted as 25,422,788, an increase of 8.6 per cent or 2,020,896 people over the previous 2016 census.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Results from the 2021 census were released to the public on 28 June 2022 from the Australian Bureau of Statistics website.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] A small amount of additional 2021 census data was released in October 2022 and in 2023.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Australia's next census is scheduled to take place in 2026.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] The census was undertaken during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] It therefore provided a clear snapshot of how the pandemic impacted Australian society.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] In Australia, completing the census is compulsory for all people in Australia on census night, only excluding foreign diplomats and their families.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Census data is used to "help governments, businesses, not-for-profit and community organisations across the country make informed decisions", including helping governments to plan the provision of services.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] An independent report from Lateral Economics found that for every $1 of investment on the census, $6 of benefits are created in the Australian economy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Since the 2001 Census, all households have the option of allowing their census data, including personal information such as names and addresses, to be stored by the National Archives of Australia (NAA) for 99 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] 99 years after Census Night, the NAA will release that data to the public in a Census Time Capsule.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Censuses stored by the NAA cannot by accessed, amended, or retrieved by anyone, including courts and tribunal, until their release, the first of which will occur in 2100.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] The 2020 Census Test occurred on 27 October 2020 with around 100,000 households from Sydney, Adelaide, Darwin, and Canberra, as well as communities in Karratha, Warrnambool, and Alice Springs Town Camps.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Every census, the ABS makes a recommendation to the Australian Government on the topics to be included, based on the benefit that data would provide to Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Through the *Census and Statistics Amendment (Statistical Information) Regulations 2020*, the federal parliament approves topics that may be included.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] For the 2021 census, the ABS had been authorised to include questions relating to long-term health conditions and service in the Australian Defence Force, and would not continue asking questions about home internet access considering the rise of mobile devices.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] This represented the first significant change to census topics since 2006.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Through late 2017, the ABS began discussions with major census data users on what was needed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] From 3 April to 30 June 2018, a formal consultation process occurred on the online "ABS Consultation Hub", with the ABS receiving 450 submissions, 315 of which were published with consent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Since 2006, the ABS has allowed the census to be completed online, moving in 2016 to be digital-first.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Like 2016, the 2021 Census was primarily collected online, with paper census forms being available on request for any household.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] In 2016, around a third of all households requested and completed their census using the paper form.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] The population counts for Australian states and territories were that New South Wales remains the most populous state, with 8,072,163 people counted, ahead of Victoria (6,503,491) and Queensland (5,156,138).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Of all residents over two-thirds (72.4% or 18,235,690) were born in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] Over a quarter of the population (27.6% or 7,502,450 persons) said they were born overseas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] After Australia, England is the most common birthplace with 927,490 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/2021-australian-census] India became the third-largest country of birth, surpassing China and New Zealand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-australians] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The ***Aboriginal Languages Act 2017*** is a New South Wales statute that is the first law in Australia to recognise the importance of the languages of the first nations people and the history of government decisions to suppress Aboriginal languages in New South Wales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The Act recognises that Aboriginal languages are part of the cultural heritage of New South Wales and Aboriginal people are the custodians of these languages and have the right to control and nurture them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The Act establishes a statutory body known as the *Aboriginal Languages Trust*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] Prior to colonisation and settlement there were many languages spoken by the Aboriginal people living in what is now known as New South Wales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The first comprehensive investigation of Australian languages was conducted by William Dawes from 1788–1791.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] In November 2016, the New South Wales Government announced that it would be pursuing legislation aimed at protecting Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The *Aboriginal Languages Bill 2017* was introduced into the NSW Legislative Council on 11 October 2017 with a traditional message stick ceremony.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The NSW *Aboriginal Languages Act 2017* became law on 24 October 2017.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] This is the first law in Australia to protect traditional Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The Act states that the objective of the *Aboriginal Languages Trust* is to "provide a focused, coordinated and sustained effort in relation to Aboriginal language activities at local, regional and State levels".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The Trust operates as a not-for-profit New South Wales government agency.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-languages-act-2017] The Trust will prepare a strategic plan to work with Aboriginal communities to help preserve and reawaken languages in New South Wales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Before British colonisation in 1803, Tasmanian Aboriginal communities maintained distinct languages, cultural traditions, and regional identities across Tasmania, with communities organised through family and clan groups connected to particular territories and seasonal movement patterns.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Estimates of the population before colonisation generally range from 3,000 to 15,000 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] During the first decades of British settlement in the 19th century, Aboriginal communities in Tasmania were devastated by introduced diseases, frontier violence, dispossession, and forced removal during the Black War.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Between 1830 and 1835, most surviving Aboriginal people were removed to the Wybalenna Aboriginal Establishment on Flinders Island in the Bass Strait.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Historians continue to debate whether these events constituted genocide under the United Nations Genocide Convention.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Tasmanian Aboriginal communities survived, particularly through descendants of Aboriginal women in Tasmania and the Bass Strait islands, and continued to maintain and revive cultural traditions and community identity.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In the 21st century, thousands of people in Tasmania identify as Aboriginal Tasmanian.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Contemporary Palawa communities continue cultural revival projects, including the reconstruction and use of palawa kani, a composite Tasmanian Aboriginal language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Aboriginal Tasmanians are the Aboriginal people of the Australian island of Tasmania, located south of the mainland.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] For much of the 20th century, the Tasmanian Aboriginal people were widely, and erroneously, thought of as extinct and intentionally exterminated by white settlers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Since the mid-1970s, Tasmanian Aboriginal activists such as Michael Mansell have sought to broaden awareness and identification of Aboriginal descent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] After campaigning by Tasmanian Aboriginal people in April 2023, UNESCO removed a document claiming they were extinct.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Contemporary figures (2016) on the number of people of Tasmanian Aboriginal descent vary depending on the criteria used to determine this identity, ranging from 6,000 to over 23,000.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] A dispute exists within the Tasmanian Aboriginal community, however, over what constitutes Aboriginality.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The Palawa, mainly descendants of white male sealers and Tasmanian Aboriginal women who settled on the Bass Strait islands, were given the power to decide who is of Tasmanian Aboriginal descent at the state level (entitlement to government Aboriginal services).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Palawa recognise only descendants of the Bass Strait Island community as Aboriginal and do not consider as Aboriginal the Lia Pootah, who claim descent, based on oral traditions, from Tasmanian mainland Aboriginal communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The Lia Pootah feel that the Palawa-controlled Tasmanian Aboriginal Centre does not represent them politically.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Since 2007, initiatives have been introduced to introduce DNA testing to establish family history within descendant subgroups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] This is strongly opposed by the Palawa and has drawn an angry reaction from some quarters, as some have claimed "spiritual connection" with Aboriginality distinct from, but not as important as, the existence of a genetic link.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The Lia Pootah object to the current test used to prove Aboriginality as they believe it favours the Palawa; a DNA test would circumvent barriers to Lia Pootah recognition, or disprove their claims to Aboriginality.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In April 2000, the Tasmanian Government's *Legislative Council Select Committee on Aboriginal Lands* discussed the difficulty of determining Aboriginality based on oral traditions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Cassandra Pybus was the claim by the Huon and Channel Aboriginal people who had an oral history of descent from two Aboriginal women.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Research found that both were non-Aboriginal convict women.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The archaeological, geographic, and linguistic record suggests successive waves of occupation in Tasmania and the coalescence of three language groups into a single broad group.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The North Midlands language has been classified as "mairremenner".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] It was spoken by the Ben Lomond and North-east nations, as well as by the Luggermairrenerpairer clan of the Central Highlands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] This language group is likely to have derived from three earlier Tasmanian languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Little is recorded about the toponymy of their country, but some local placenames have survived and are likely to belong to the "Nara" language group.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Much of what is known about the original Tasmanian Aboriginal languages survives through fragmentary wordlists recorded by European visitors, explorers and colonists between the late eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Because many languages disappeared before systematic documentation occurred, linguists disagree on the exact number and classification of Tasmanian languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The surviving records were compiled using inconsistent spellings and transcription methods, making reconstruction difficult.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] More than twenty individuals documented words and phrases during the colonial period, including English, Scottish, Danish, and French recorders.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] There are no living speakers of the original Tasmanian languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Spoken recordings are extremely rare, with the best-known examples being recordings of Fanny Cochrane Smith singing traditional songs in 1899 and 1903.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Smith is often described as the last fluent speaker of a Tasmanian Aboriginal language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] By the late nineteenth century, only fragmentary records of the original languages remained.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Some language groups had already been severely affected by introduced diseases before large-scale British settlement began in 1803.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] As Aboriginal communities were displaced and reduced in number during the colonial period, many languages disappeared before they could be properly documented.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Although the original Tasmanian Aboriginal languages are no longer spoken fluently, some words survived among Palawa communities descended from Tasmanian Aboriginal women and European sealers in the Furneaux Islands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In recent decades, efforts to reconstruct and revive elements of the languages have continued through the development of Palawa kani, a reconstructed language created from surviving historical wordlists and linguistic records.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Aboriginal Tasmanians were primarily nomadic people who lived in adjoining territories, moving based on seasonal changes in food supplies such as seafood, land mammals, and native vegetables and berries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Approximately 4,000 years ago, Aboriginal Tasmanians largely dropped scaled fish from their diet, and began eating more land mammals, such as possums, kangaroos, and wallabies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Aboriginal Tasmanians had employed bone tools, but it appears that they switched from worked bone tools to more efficient sharpened stone tools.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The significance of the disappearance of bone tools (believed to have been primarily used for fishing) and fish in the diet is heavily debated.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Some argue that it is evidence of a maladaptive society, while others argue that the change was economic, as large areas of scrub at that time were changing to grassland, providing substantially increased food resources.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Fish were never a large part of the diet, ranking behind shellfish and seals, and with more resources available, the cost/benefit ratio of fishing may have become too high.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Archaeological evidence indicates that around the time these changes occurred, the Tasmanian people began expanding their territories, a process that continued when Europeans arrived.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Aboriginal Tasmanians crossed into what is now Tasmania approximately 35,000 years ago during the Late Pleistocene, when lower sea levels during the Last Glacial Period exposed the Bassian Plain, a broad land bridge linking Tasmania to mainland Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Archaeological evidence suggests that Tasmania was colonised by successive waves of Aboriginal people from southern Australia during periods of lower sea level associated with glacial maxima.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Archaeological and geographic evidence indicate that Aboriginal Tasmanians and their ancestors lived in a colder and drier environment than exists today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] During glacial periods, arid conditions extended from southern Australia into the midlands of central Tasmania, interrupted by warmer and wetter intervals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] People moving into Tasmania would have crossed stretches of seawater and dry country before reaching more habitable environments, including the highlands of what is now King Island in Bass Strait.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Evidence from caves and occupation sites across Tasmania demonstrates long-term Aboriginal occupation during the Pleistocene.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Excavations at Warreen Cave in southwest Tasmania demonstrated occupation from as early as 34,000 BP (approximately 32,000 BCE), making Aboriginal Tasmanians among the southernmost known human populations in the world during the Pleistocene era.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Archaeological investigations in southwest and central Tasmania, including the island's highland regions, also produced evidence dating from approximately 35,000 to 11,000 BP (about 33,000-9,000 BCE), providing some of the richest archaeological evidence from Pleistocene Greater Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Deposits dating to approximately 19,000 years ago at Kutikina, or Fraser Cave, in western Tasmania, demonstrate continued occupation of Tasmania's highlands during the Ice Age and Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Oral traditions have also been studied alongside archaeological evidence in research into the environmental history of the Bassian Plain and the formation of Bass Strait.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Between about 14,000 and 12,000 BCE, rising sea levels submerged the Bassian Plain and formed Bass Strait, separating Tasmania from mainland Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Aboriginal Tasmanians remained isolated from mainland Aboriginal populations for approximately 8,000 years, until European exploration in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Archaeological evidence suggests that small Aboriginal Tasmanian populations living on the highlands of what are now King Island and the Furneaux Group became stranded by rising waters after the formation of Bass Strait and later died out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Abel Tasman, credited as the first European to discover Tasmania (in 1642) and who named it Van Diemen's Land, did not encounter any of the Aboriginal Tasmanians when he landed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In 1772, a French exploratory expedition under Marion Dufresne visited Tasmania.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] At first, contact with the Aboriginal people was friendly; however, the Aboriginal Tasmanians became alarmed when another boat was dispatched towards the shore.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] It was reported that spears and stones were thrown, and the French responded with musket fire, killing at least one Aboriginal person and wounding several others.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Two later French expeditions, led by Bruni d'Entrecasteaux in 1792–93 and Nicolas Baudin in 1802, made friendly contact with the Aboriginal Tasmanians; the d'Entrecasteaux expedition did so over an extended period.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The *Resolution* under Captain Tobias Furneaux (part of an expedition led by Captain James Cook) had visited in 1773 but made no contact with the Aboriginal Tasmanians, although gifts were left for them in unoccupied shelters found on Bruny Island.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The first known British contact with the Aboriginal Tasmanians was on Bruny Island by Captain Cook in 1777.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Captain William Bligh also visited Bruny Island in 1788 and made peaceful contact with the Aboriginal Tasmanians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] More extensive contact between Aboriginal Tasmanians and Europeans resulted when British and American seal hunters began visiting the islands in Bass Strait as well as the northern and eastern coasts of Tasmania from the late 1790s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Shortly thereafter (by about 1800), sealers were regularly left on uninhabited islands in Bass Strait during the sealing season (November to May).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The sealers established semi-permanent camps or settlements on the islands, which were close enough for the sealers to reach the main island of Tasmania in small boats and so make contact with the Aboriginal Tasmanians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Trading relationships developed between sealers and Tasmanian Aboriginal tribes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Hunting dogs became highly prized by the Aboriginal people, as were other exotic items such as flour, tea, and tobacco.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The Aboriginal people traded kangaroo skins for such goods.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] A trade in Aboriginal women soon developed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Many Tasmanian Aboriginal women were highly skilled in hunting seals, as well as in obtaining other foods such as seabirds, and some Tasmanian tribes would trade their services and, more rarely, those of Aboriginal men to the sealers for the seal-hunting season.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] This trade involved not only women of the tribe engaged in it but also women abducted from other tribes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Some may have been given to incorporate the new arrivals into Aboriginal society through marriage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Sealers engaged in raids along the coasts to abduct Aboriginal women and were reported to have killed Aboriginal men in the process.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Bonwick also reports a number of claims of brutality by sealers towards Aboriginal women, including some of those made by Robinson.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Sealing captain James Kelly wrote in 1816 that the custom of the sealers was to each have "two to five of these native women for their own use and benefit".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] A shortage of women available "in trade" resulted in abduction becoming common, and, in 1830, it was reported that at least fifty Aboriginal women were "kept in slavery" on the Bass Strait islands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Some of the women were taken back to the islands by the sealers involuntarily and some went willingly, as in the case of a woman called Tarenorerer (Eng: Walyer).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Differing opinions have been given on Walyer's involvement with the sealers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] McFarlane writes that she voluntarily joined the sealers with members of her family and was responsible for attacking Aboriginal people and white settlers alike.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Ryan comes to a different conclusion, that Walyer had been abducted at Port Sorell by Aboriginal people and traded to the sealers for dogs and flour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Walyer was later to gain some notoriety for her attempts to kill the sealers to escape their brutality.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Walyer, a Punnilerpanner, joined the Plairhekehillerplue band after eventually escaping and went on to lead attacks on employees of the Van Diemen's Land Company.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Walyer's attacks are the first recorded use of muskets by Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Captured, she refused to work and was banished to Penguin Island.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Later imprisoned on Swan Island, she attempted to organise a rebellion.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Although Aboriginal women were by custom forbidden to take part in war, several Aboriginal women who escaped from sealers became leaders or took part in attacks.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] According to Lyndall Ryan, the women traded to or kidnapped by sealers became "a significant dissident group" against European/white authority.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] There are numerous stories of the sealers' brutality towards the Aboriginal women, with some of these reports originating from Robinson.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In 1830, Robinson seized fourteen Aboriginal women from the sealers, planning for them to marry Aboriginal men at the Flinders Island settlement.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Josephine Flood, an archaeologist specialising in Australian mainland Aboriginal peoples, notes: "he encountered strong resistance from the women as well as sealers".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The sealers sent a representative, James Munro, to appeal to Governor George Arthur and argue for the women's return, on the basis that they wanted to stay with their sealer husbands and children rather than marry Aboriginal men unknown to them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Arthur ordered the return of some of the women.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Shortly thereafter, Robinson began to disseminate stories, told to him by James Munro, of atrocities allegedly committed by the sealers against Aboriginal people, and against Aboriginal women in particular.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Brian Plomley, who edited Robinson's papers, expressed scepticism about these atrocities and notes that they were not reported to Archdeacon William Broughton's 1830 committee of inquiry into violence towards Tasmanians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Abduction and ill-treatment of Aboriginal Tasmanians certainly occurred, but the extent is debated.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] However, a mixed-race community of partial Tasmanian Aboriginal descent formed on the Islands, where it remains to the present, and many modern day Aboriginal Tasmanians trace their descent from the 19th century sealer communities of Bass Strait.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Although commercial sealing on Van Diemen's Land had begun in late 1798, the first significant European presence on the island came in September 1803 with the establishment of a small British military outpost at Risdon Cove on the Derwent River near present-day Hobart.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The British had several hostile encounters with Aboriginal clans over the next five months, with shots fired and an Aboriginal boy abducted.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] David Collins arrived as the colony's first lieutenant governor in February 1804 with instructions from London that any acts of violence against the Aboriginal people were to be punished.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] But he failed to publish those instructions, leaving a legal framework unclear for dealing with any violent conflict.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] On 3 May 1804, soldiers, settlers, and convicts from Risdon Cove fired on a hunting party of 100 to 300 Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The British commanding officer stated that he thought the Aboriginal group was hostile.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Witnesses to the massacre stated that between three and fifty Aboriginal men, women, and children had died.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] A boy whose parents were killed in the massacre was taken and given the name Robert Hobart May.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] This boy became the first Aboriginal Tasmanian to have extended contact with the British colonial society.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Between 1803 and 1823, there were two phases of conflict between the Aboriginal people and the British colonists.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] These practices also increased conflict among the men of different Aboriginal tribes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] This, in turn, led to a decline in the Aboriginal population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Historian Lyndall Ryan records that 74 Aboriginal people (almost all women) lived with sealers on the Bass Strait islands up to 1835.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] By 1816, the kidnapping of Aboriginal children for labour had become widespread.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] A number of young Aboriginal children were known to be living with settlers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] An Irish sealer named Brien spared the life of the baby son of a native woman he had abducted, explaining, "as (he) had stolen the dam he would keep the cub".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] When the child grew up he became an invaluable assistant to Brien but was considered "no good" by his own people as he was brought up to dislike Aboriginal people, whom he considered "dirty lazy brutes".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Twenty-six were definitely known (through baptismal records) to have been taken into settlers' homes as infants or very small children, too young to be of service as labourers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Some Aboriginal children were sent to the Orphan School in Hobart.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Lyndall Ryan reports fifty-eight Aboriginal people, of various ages, living with settlers in Tasmania in the period up to 1835.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Some historians argue that European disease did not appear to be a serious factor until after 1829.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Other historians, including Geoffrey Blainey and Keith Windschuttle, point to introduced disease as the main cause of the destruction of the full-blooded Tasmanian Aboriginal population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The work of historian James Bonwick and anthropologist H.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Introduced venereal disease not only directly caused deaths but, more insidiously, left a significant percentage of the population unable to reproduce.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Bonwick also recorded a strong Aboriginal oral tradition of an epidemic even before formal colonisation in 1803.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] "According to Calder, a rapid and remarkable declension of the numbers of the Aborigines had been going on long before the remnants were gathered together on Flinders Island.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Whole tribes (some of which Robinson mentions by name as being in existence fifteen or twenty years before he went amongst them, and which probably never had a shot fired at them) had absolutely and entirely vanished.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] To the causes to which he attributes this strange wasting away ...
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] I think infecundity, produced by the infidelity of the women to their husbands in the early times of the colony, may be safely added ...
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Robinson recorded in his journals a number of comments regarding the Aboriginal Tasmanians' susceptibility to diseases, particularly respiratory diseases.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In 1832, he revisited the west coast of Tasmania, far from the settled regions, and wrote: "The numbers of Aborigines along the western coast have been considerably reduced since the time of my last visit [1830].
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Between 1825 and 1831, a pattern of guerilla warfare by the Aboriginal Tasmanians was identified by the colonists.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Rapid pastoral expansion, a depletion of native game, and an increase in the colony's population triggered Aboriginal resistance from 1824 onwards, when it is estimated by Lyndall Ryan that 1,000 Aboriginal people remained in the settled districts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The official Government position was that Aboriginal people were blameless for any hostilities, but when Musquito was hanged in 1825, a significant debate was generated which split the colonists along class lines.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The "higher grade" saw the hanging as a dangerous precedent and argued that Aboriginal people were only defending their land and should not be punished for doing so.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The "lower grade" of colonists wanted more Aboriginal people hanged to encourage a "conciliatory line of conduct".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Governor Arthur sided with the "lower grade," and 1825 saw the first official acceptance that Aboriginal people were at least partly to blame for conflict.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In 1826, the Government gazette, which had formerly reported "retaliatory actions" by Aboriginal people, now reported "acts of atrocity" and for the first time used the terminology "Aborigine" instead of "native".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] A newspaper reported that there were only two solutions to the problem: either they should be "hunted down like wild beasts and destroyed," or they should be removed from the settled districts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The colonial Government assigned troops to drive them out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] A Royal Proclamation in 1828 established military posts on the boundaries, and a further proclamation declared martial law against the Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Every dispatch from Governor Arthur to the Secretary of State during this period stressed that in every case where Aboriginal people had been killed, it was colonists who initiated hostilities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Though many Aboriginal deaths went unrecorded, the Cape Grim massacre in 1828 demonstrates the level of frontier violence towards Aboriginal Tasmanians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The Black War of 1828–1832 and the Black Line of 1830 were turning points in the relationship with European settlers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Even though many of the Aboriginal people managed to avoid capture during these events, they were shaken by the size of the campaigns against them, and this brought them to a position where they were willing to surrender to Robinson and move to Flinders Island.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] European and Aboriginal casualties, including the Aboriginal residents who were captured, may be considered reasonably accurate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The figures for the Aboriginal population shot is likely a substantial undercount.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In late 1831, Robinson brought the first 51 Aboriginal people to a settlement on Flinders Island called The Lagoons, which proved inadequate because it was exposed to gales, had little water, and had no land suitable for cultivation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Supplies to the settlement were inadequate, and if sealers had not supplied potatoes, the Aboriginal people would have starved.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The Europeans were living on oatmeal and potatoes while the Aboriginal people, who detested oatmeal and refused to eat it, survived on potatoes and rice supplemented by mutton birds they caught.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Within months 31 Aboriginal people had died.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] By January 1832, a further 44 captured Aboriginal residents had arrived, and conflicts arose between the tribal groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In October 1832, it was decided to build a new camp with better buildings (wattle and daub) at a more suitable location, Pea Jacket Point.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Pea Jacket Point was renamed Civilisation Point but became more commonly known as the Wybalenna Aboriginal Establishment.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Wybalenna in the Ben Lomond language meant "dwellings" but is generally translated as "black man's houses".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] By 1835, the living conditions had deteriorated to the extent that in October, Robinson personally took charge of Wybalenna, organising better food and improving the housing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] However, of the 220 who arrived with Robinson, most died in the following 14 years from introduced disease and inadequate shelter.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] As a result of their loss of freedom, the birth rate was extremely low, and few children survived infancy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] To defuse the situation, Sergeant Wight took the Big River group to Green Island, where they were abandoned, and he later decided to move the rest to Green Island as well.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Two weeks later, Robinson arrived with Lieutenant Darling, the new station commander, and moved the Aboriginal people back to The Lagoons.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Darling ensured a supply of plentiful food and permitted "hunting excursions".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] After arrival, all Aboriginal children aged between six and 15 years were removed from their families to be brought up by the storekeeper and a lay preacher.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Convicts were assigned to build housing and do most of the work at the settlement, including the growing of food in the vegetable gardens.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In 1839, Governor Franklin appointed a board to inquire into conditions at Wybalenna, which rejected Robinson's claims of improved living conditions and found the settlement a failure.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The report was never released, and the government continued to promote Wybalenna as a success in the treatment of Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The Aboriginal people were free to roam the island and were often absent from the settlement for extended periods on hunting trips as the rations supplied turned out to be inadequate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In March 1847 six Aboriginal people at Wybalenna presented a petition to Queen Victoria, the first petition to a reigning monarch from any Aboriginal group in Australia, requesting that the promises made to them be honoured.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] According to the guards, the Aboriginal people developed "too much independence" by trying to continue their culture, which they considered "recklessness" and "rank ingratitude".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] In October 1847, the 47 survivors were transferred to their final settlement at Oyster Cove station.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Only 44 survived the trip (11 couples, 12 single men and 10 children) and the children were immediately sent to the orphan school in Hobart.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Although the housing and food were better than Wybalenna, the station was a former convict station that had been abandoned earlier that year due to health issues, as it was located on inadequately drained mudflats.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Their numbers continued to diminish, being estimated at around a dozen in 1859, and by 1869 there was only one, who died in 1876.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The social organisation of Aboriginal Tasmanians had at least two hierarchies: the domestic unit or family group and the social unit or clan, which had a self-defining name with 40 to 50 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] It is contentious whether there was a larger political organisation, hitherto described as a "tribe" in the literature (and by colonial observers), as there is no evidence in the historical literature of larger political entities above that of the clan.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Robinson, who gathered ethnographic data in the early 1800s, described Aboriginal political groups at the clan level only.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Nevertheless, clans that shared a geographic region and language group are now usually classified by modern ethnographers as a nation, the Palawa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] According to Ryan, the population of Tasmania was aligned into nine nations composed of six to fifteen clans each, with each clan comprising two to six extended family units who were relations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Individual clans ranged over a defined nation boundary with elaborate rites of entry required of visitors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] There were more than 60 clans before European colonisation, although only 48 have been located and associated with particular territories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] They socialised, intermarried, and fought "wars" against other clans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Estimates of the combined population of Aboriginal people in Tasmania before European arrival range from 3,000 to 15,000.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Genetic studies have suggested much higher figures, which is supported by oral traditions that Aboriginal people were "more numerous than the white people were aware of" but that their population had been greatly reduced by a sudden outbreak of disease before 1803.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] It is speculated that early contacts with sealers before colonisation had resulted in an epidemic.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] Using archaeological evidence, Stockton (I983:68) estimated 3,000 to 6,000 for the northern half of the west coast alone, or up to six times the commonly accepted estimate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] He later revised this to 3,000 to 5,000 for the entire island, based on historical sources.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] The low rate of genetic drift indicates that Stockton's original maximum estimate is likely the lower boundary and, while not indicated by the archaeological record, a population as high as 100,000 can "not be rejected out of hand".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p01] This is supported by carrying capacity data indicating greater resource productivity in Tasmania than on the mainland.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The location and migratory patterns discussed below are based on the work of Jones (cited in Tindale).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Ryan used Jones' work in her seminal history of Aboriginal Tasmanians, but Taylor discusses in his thesis how Jones' original work is uncited and possibly conjectural.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Moreover, Jones published his work without recourse to Plomley's later extensive descriptions of Tasmanian Aboriginal clan groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Given this, the clan boundaries and nomadic patterns discussed below should be treated with caution unless supported by primary documents.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Little is known of specific sites of significance to the Letteremairrener, but contemporary Palawa assert the significance of the Cataract Gorge as a place of ceremony and significance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Certainly, in 1847, when a surviving Aboriginal "chief" was temporarily returned to Launceston from exile in Wybalenna, he requested to be taken to the Cataract Gorge and was described as being jubilant at return to the Gorge, followed with apparent lamentation at what had been lost to him.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] There are no recorded significant archaeological remains in the Gorge precinct, although the area was subject to significant seasonal flooding before damming.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Letteremairrener had been recorded to have specific meeting places at Paterson's Plains (near modern-day St Leonards) and groups as large as 150 had been recorded in colonial times in this vicinity.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The clan country overlapped with that of the Panninher and Tyrrernotepanner, and it is likely that, at times, the clans shared resources across clan borders.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The North Midlands nation was circumscribed by the valley's geographical constraints.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The occupation of the western Tamar is open to dispute – the ethnographic record suggests that it was the province of the Pallitorre and Parnillerpanner clans of the North nation, or the Leterrmairrener, or a hitherto unnamed clan of the North Midlands nation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] It is likely that the west Tamar valley, or the Meander river valley formed the NNW boundaries of the North Midlands nation – with the arc of highlands formed by Cluan Tier and Dry's Bluff forming the northwestern extremity of their country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] To the east, the natural boundary was the South-Esk River and, running northwards, the high tier of Mts Barrow, Arthur, and Tippogoree Hills: beyond which lay the North-east nation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Running south past the eastern bend of the South-Esk, it appears that the North Midlands Nation held land to some extent along the south bank of the Esk, at least as far as Avoca and possibly as far as the natural boundary of the St Pauls River, beyond which the Oyster Bay nation were resident.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] To the south, their country was constrained by the uplands beyond Tunbridge, as the plains narrowed towards Big River and Oyster Bay country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The North Midlands nation occupied the Midland plains, a major geographical area formed in a horst and graben valley which was also subject to previous major freshwater lacustrine inundation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The result was a relatively flat and fertile landscape that supported a large biomass, thus being a major food source for the Aboriginal peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Letteremairrener (Letter-ramare-ru-nah) clan occupied the country from Low Head to modern-day Launceston.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] In colonial times, reports were made of clusters of huts, up to ten in number, in the Tamar valley, and there are extensive archaeological remains of occupation on both sides of the Tamar river and the north coastal country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] While little is known with certainty about seasonal movements, historical accounts indicate that several Big River clans travelled eastward through Oyster Bay territory along the Derwent River to reach coastal camps near Pitt Water.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Reciprocal movement rights between Big River and Oyster Bay peoples are also recorded, reflecting shared access arrangements rather than rigid territorial boundaries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Big River people are an Aboriginal group described in early colonial and ethnographic sources as being associated with the Central Highlands and upper river systems of central Tasmania, including the Ouse, Clyde, and Dee rivers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Their country contained the most important ochre mines in Tasmania, accessed by well-defined roads kept open by firing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] They traded the ochre with nearby clanspeople.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] They would spend part of the year in the country of the North West nation to hunt seals and collect shells from Robbins Island for necklaces.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Relatively isolated, the region was first explored by Europeans in 1824, when the Van Diemen's Land Company was granted 250,000 acres (100,000 ha), including the greater part of the clan's hunting grounds.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The settlement was a failure, with the inland areas described as "wet, cold and soggy", while the coastal region was difficult to clear, as Superintendent Henry Hellyer noted the "forest [was] altogether unlike anything I have seen in the Island".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] However, in 1827, a port was established at Emu Bay.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] In 1828, Tarerenorerer (English name: Walyer), a woman who had escaped from sealers, became the leader of the Emu Bay people and attacked the settlers with stolen weapons, the first recorded use of muskets by Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Panninher (parn-in-her) were known to colonial people as the Penny Royal Creek tribe, named eponymously after the river that flows from the Western Tiers south of Drys Bluff (now called the Liffey River).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Panninher named the Liffey river *tellerpanger* and Drys Bluff, the mountain rearing above their homeland, was *taytitkekitheker*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Their territory broadly covered the north plains of the midlands, from the west bank of the Tamar River across to what is now Evandale, and terminated at the Tyerrernotepanner country around modern-day Conara.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Panninher also freely moved from the Tamar to the central highlands and brokered trade in ochre from the Toolumbunner mine to neighbouring clans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Robinson describes the road used by the Panninher from their home up to the Central Highlands, via the gully of the Liffey River, and the South road along the base of the Western Tiers – up the Lake River to modern-day Interlaken.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Whilst sites of ritual significance to the Panninher are not known, the Panninher were known to frequent Native Point, on the South Esk River between modern day Perth and Evandale, where flint quarries were located and clans met for celebration.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Here local historians believe that cemetery (hollowed) trees were used to inter the dead.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Similarly, Reibey's Ford, near modern-day Hadspen, was a known "resort of the natives" and they named this site *moorronnoe*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Archaeological evidence also indicates signs of continuous occupation at permanent lagoons near Cleveland, which was known historically as a clan meeting place.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Panninher were affected early by settlement around Norfolk Plains, and aggressive assertion of property rights by settlers at first hindered their hunting and migration through their country and, subsequently, led to outright hostility from both parties.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Captain Ritchie, an early settler near Perth, tolerated, or fostered, forays by his assigned men against the Panninher, and this culminated in a massacre by settlers near modern-day Cressy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Panninher, or their neighbouring clansmen, retaliated in various attacks against settlers at Western Lagoon and in remote country up the Lake River, reaching a peak in aggression against the colonial interlopers by 1827.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] In 1831, a war party of "100 or 150 stout men" attacked settlers at the base of the Western Tiers and up the Lake River, but it is unclear whether this was the action of the Panninher alone or a confederation of warriors from remnant North Tasmanian nations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The colonial settlers made little distinction between Panninher and members of the "Stony Creek tribe," and it is likely that the North Midlands nation had disintegrated, with the amalgamated band known by this time as the "Stony Creek tribe" under the overarching name.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] This notwithstanding, it seems that the Panninher were resourceful enough to survive in some numbers until late in the Black War.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The members of the Paredarerme nation had good relations with the Big River nation, with large congregations at favoured hunting sites inland and at the coast.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Relations with the North Midlands nation were mostly hostile, and evidence suggests that the Douglas-Apsley region may have been a dangerous borderland rarely visited (Ferguson 1986 p.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Generally, the clans of the Paredarerme ranged inland to the High Country for spring and summer and returned to the coast for autumn and winter, but not all people left their territory each year with some deciding to stay by the coast.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Migrations provided a varied diet with plentiful seafood, seals and birds on the coast, and good hunting for kangaroos, wallabies and possums inland.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The High Country also provided opportunities to trade for ochre with the North-west and North people, and to harvest intoxicating gum from *Eucalyptus gunnii*, found only on the plateau.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The key determinant of camp sites was topography.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The majority of camps were along river valleys, adjacent north-facing hill slopes, and on gentle slopes bordering a forest or marsh (Brown 1986).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The clan Tyerrernotepanner was centred at Campbell Town and was one of up to four clans in the south central Midlands area.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Nevertheless, this clan name is now used as a general term for all Aboriginal peoples of this region.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Lake Leake (previously Kearney's Bogs), Campbell Town, Ellinthorpe Plains (near modern-day Auburn), and Tooms Lake were described as "resorts of the natives" by settlers and showed substantial evidence of seasonal occupation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Furthermore, several small lagoons in the midlands area all show substantial archaeological evidence of regular occupation consistent with tool-making and semi-nomadic use.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Aboriginal roads, *markenner*, are described as passing up the Eastern Tiers to Swanport, up the Western Tier to Interlaken, and up the Lake River to Woods Lake and thence to the Central Highlands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Ben Lomond nation occupied the 260 km2 of country surrounding the Ben Lomond plateau.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Plangermaireener is also used as a blanket term for the Ben Lomond nation, which reflects the suffix "mairreener"; meaning "people".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] This notwithstanding, the Palawa were a nomadic people and likely occupied these lands seasonally.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The clans of the Ben Lomond nation were nomadic, and the Aboriginal residents hunted along the valleys of the South Esk and North Esk rivers, their tributaries, and the highlands to the northeast; as well as making forays to the plateau in summer.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] There are records of Aboriginal huts or dwellings around the foothills of Stacks Bluff and around the headwaters of the South Esk River near modern-day Mathinna.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] On the plateau, there is evidence of artifacts around Lake Youl that suggests regular occupation of this site by Aboriginal peoples after the last ice age.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The clans of the Ben Lomond nation had close enough relationships with neighbouring clans of the East Coast and North Midlands that they enjoyed seasonal foraging rights to these adjoining territories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The North West nation had good relations with the North nation, who were allowed access to the resources of the north-west coast.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] First explored by Europeans in 1824, the region was considered inhospitable and only lightly settled, although it suffered a high rate of Aboriginal dispossession and killings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The first European settlement in Tasmania, at Risdon Cove, was established on land belonging to the Aboriginal people of the South East region.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The region contained some of Tasmania's most important mining sites for materials such as silcrete, chert, and quartzite.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The South East people are recorded as having a hostile relationship with the Oyster Bay nation to their north, including raids that reportedly involved the abduction of women.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The following table reflects groups recorded historically in the South East.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Some names, such as "Mouheneenner", reflect terms used in early colonial records and may not reflect the names people used themselves.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Contemporary understanding and use of language and group names continue to evolve through community-led cultural revitalisation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Paredarerme was estimated to be the largest Tasmanian nation with ten clans totalling 700 to 800 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The North East nation consisted of seven clans totalling around 500 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] They had good relations with the Ben Lomond nation and were granted seasonal access to the resources of the north-east coast.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Northern nation consisted of four clans totalling 200–300 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] These sources record the group as comprising several smaller clans, whose names and territorial associations were inconsistently documented, and often phonetically, by European observers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Population estimates from the early nineteenth century suggest approximately 400–500 people across five principal clans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Some nineteenth- and early twentieth-century sources use the term *Mairremmener* (with variant spellings) as a broader or imprecise label for inland Aboriginal groups associated with the Big River region, rather than as a discrete clan name.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Usage of the term varies across historical literature and does not correspond neatly with the individual clan names recorded elsewhere in colonial accounts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The following table summarises clan names and associated areas as recorded in early colonial and ethnographic sources, with modern townships listed for geographic reference only.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The North Midlands nation is likely to have consisted of several clans, but there are three accepted major clan divisions described in the ethnographic literature today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The total population of the North Midlands nation has been estimated to be between 300 and 500 and, although migratory, the archaeological and historical record infers seasonal residency in locations adjacent to permanent water sources in the Midlands valley.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Three major national divisions are generally ascribed to the North Midlands nation, although it is likely that more clans existed, and Ryan (2012) asserts the possibility of another two clan territories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] What is known of the composition of the North Midlands nation derives from settler description (who ascribed simple tribal divisions based upon locality) and direct attribution from contemporary Aboriginal Tasmanians (recorded by Robinson, collated by Plomley) and later researched by Rhys Jones.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] From this, we can be certain that there were three major clan divisions, described by colonials as the Port Dalrymple tribe (Leterrermairrener clan), at the Tamar River; the Pennyroyal Creek tribe (Panninher), at Norfolk Plains; and the Stony Creek tribe (Tyrrernotepanner), at Campbell Town.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Letteremairrener were among the first Aboriginal peoples to be affected by the impact of colonisation by the British as colonial occupation commenced at Port Dalrymple and progressed to Launceston, with settlers progressively occupying land up the Tamar valley.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] By the early 1800s, the Letteremairrener had been involved in skirmishes with colonial exploratory parties.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] In the second decade of that century, they had reached some accommodation with the interlopers and were observed practising spear throwing near present-day Paterson Barracks and watching colonial women wash clothes at Cataract Gorge.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Between 1811 and 1827, several Aboriginal children were baptised in Launceston, either abducted or the progeny of settler/Aboriginal liaisons.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] By 1830, the people of the Letteremairenner had largely disappeared from their homeland, and the survivors were waging a desperate guerrilla war against the British colonists, living a fringe existence in Launceston or on the margins of their traditional land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] By 1837, the Letteremairrenner had disappeared completely from the Tamar Valley and would eventually die in the squalor of Wybalenna or Oyster Cove.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Tyerrernotepanner (Chera-noti-pana) were known to colonial people as the Stony Creek tribe, named eponymously from the small southern tributary of the South Esk at Llewellyn, west of modern-day Avoca.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The clan Tyerrernotepanner was one of up to four clans in the south central Midlands area.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The clan divisions of the southern central Midlands are suggested below.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Caution must be exercised as to the provenance of the names and the complete accuracy of attributing discrete geographical regions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Tyerrernotepanner are consistently described in contemporary records as a "fierce tribe," and these records document concerted and sustained violence by the Tyerrernotepanner during the Black War.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Tyeerrernotepanner, along with clansmen from other remnant tribes, conducted raids across the midlands during the Black War and, until "conciliated" by Robinson, were the subject of fearful reminiscence by colonial people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The famed Aboriginal leader Umarrah was a member of this clan, and he was noted for his aggression and sustained campaign against European interlopers - although he was raised by colonials himself.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Ben Lomond nation consisted of at least three clans totalling 150–200 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] They occupied the 260 km2 of country surrounding the Ben Lomond plateau.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Three clan names are known, but their locations are somewhat conjectural – the clans were recorded as Plangermaireener, Plindermairhemener, and Tonenerweenerlarmenne.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Ben Lomond nation is sometimes described as the Ben Lomond/Pennyroyal Creek nation from an entry in Robinson's journal: "(Mannalargenna) ... said that 'the smoke...was that of the Ben Lomond-Pennyroyal Creek natives'".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] This is a misnomer, as the Pennyroyal Creek was the original European name for the Liffey River and the Pennyroyal Creek tribe was the contemporary name of the Panninher clan of the North Midlands nation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Mannalargenna would be familiar with the clans neighbouring his own traditional country and could be relied upon to report accurately the composition of the clanspeople in question.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] It is plausible that when Robinson was writing in 1830, the remnant peoples of the Ben Lomond nation had federated with that of the Panninher, and this was the provenance of the conjoined title.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The North West nation numbered between 400 and 600 people at the time of contact with Europeans and had at least eight clans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] They had good relations with the North nation, who were allowed access to the resources of the north-west coast.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Eyewitness accounts suggest the South East nation may have comprised up to ten clans, with an estimated population of around 500 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] However, by the time George Augustus Robinson began documenting his journals in 1829, only four groups totalling approximately 160–200 individuals were officially recorded.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] By then, much of the South East territory had been colonised, leading to displacement and severe depletion of traditional food sources.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Truganini belonged to the Nuenonne people of Bruny Island, known traditionally as *Lunawanna-alonnah*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The first European settlements on the island were named Lunawanna and Alonnah, and many of the island's landmarks continue to bear Nuenonne names.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Aboriginal culture was disrupted severely in the 19th century after the dispossession of land and the incarceration of Aboriginal people on Wybalenna and Oyster Cove.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Much traditional knowledge has irrevocably disappeared, and what remains has been nurtured over several generations, starting with the Aboriginal wives of sealers on the Furneaux Islands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] But, as the Aboriginal writer Greg Lehman states, "Aboriginal culture (is not) past tense." Aboriginal people, in a variety of forms, continue to express their culture in unique ways – expressing themes that lament the past but also celebrate the endurance and continuity of culture into the future.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The mythology of the Aboriginal Tasmanians appears to be complex and possibly specific to each clan group.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] One of their creation myths refers to two creator deities, Moinee and Droemerdene; the children of Parnuen, the sun, and Vena, the moon.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Moinee appears as the primeval creator, forming the land and rivers of Tasmania and fashioning the first man, Parlevar – embodied from a spirit residing in the ground.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] This form was similar to a kangaroo, and Aboriginal people consequently take the kangaroo as a totem.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Similarly, Moinee then created the kangaroo, who emerged, like the first man, from the soil.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Droemerdene appears as the star Canopus, who helped the first men to change from their kangaroo-like form.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] He removed their tails and fashioned their knee joints "so that they could rest," and thus man achieved differentiation from the kangaroo.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Moinee fought with his brother Droemerdene, and many "devils", after Droemerdene changed the shape of the first men, and Moinee was finally hurled to his death from the sky to take form as a standing stone at Cox Bight.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Droemerdene subsequently fell into the sea at Louisa Bay.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Toogee Low (Port Davey) remained in mythology as a residence of many "devils".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Little has been recorded of traditional Tasmanian Aboriginal spiritual life.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Colonial British sources recorded that Aboriginal people described topographical features, such as valleys and caves, as inhabited by spiritual entities, contemporaries referring to them as "sprites".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Furthermore, Robinson recorded that members of some clans held an animistic regard for certain species of trees within their domain.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Robinson recorded several discussions about spiritual entities that his companions described as having agency or a source of interpretive power to aid in navigating their physical world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Tasmanian Aboriginal people would describe these entities as "devils" and related that these spiritual beings would walk alongside Aboriginal people, "carrying a torch but could not be seen".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Mannarlargenna, in particular, described consulting his "devil," which seems to be a resident personal spirituality that provided prognostic or oracular powers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The "devil" might also be used to describe malevolent spiritual entities in the Aboriginal cosmos.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Aboriginal people recounted that there was a prime malevolent spirit called *rageowrapper*, who appeared as a large black (Aboriginal?) man and is associated with the darkness.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] *Rageowrapper* might appear borne on a strong wind or be the source of severe illness; this malign spirit might be released from a sick individual by cutting the skin to "let him out".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Several researchers assert that there was a belief in a Manichaean cosmos with a "good" and "bad" spirit, delineated by day and night, although this may reflect the observers' cultural bias.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Milligan (a contemporary at Wyballenna) described a creator spirit called *tiggana marrabona* – translating as "twilight man" but, as referred to above, there are a number of supernatural beings associated with creation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Traditional Aboriginal Tasmanians also related beliefs of a spiritual afterlife.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] One such belief, related by an Aboriginal person from the west coast nation, was that the spirit of the dead travelled to a place over the sea: to the far north-west, called *Moo-ai*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Other references are made to an Island of the Dead, *tini drini*, described as "an island in Bass Strait" where the dead would be reincarnated or "jump up white men".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] White here does not refer to European, but rather the skeletal or phantasmic nature of the returned dead.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The dead might be cremated or interred in a hollow tree or rock grave, depending on clan custom.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Aboriginal people were also recorded to keep bones of dead people as talismans or amulets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The bones might be worn on a kangaroo sinew string bare around the neck or enclosed in a kangaroo skin bag.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Traditional Aboriginal Tasmanians saw the night sky as the residence of creator spirits (see above) and also described constellations that represent tribal life, such as figures of fighting men and courting couples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Tasmanian Aboriginal peoples used bark wrapping to protect fire-starting coals from Tasmania's wet maritime climate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] When their last coal was extinguished, they would ask fire from neighbouring hearths or clans, but also probably used friction fire-starting methods and possibly mineral percussion, despite claims that the native Tasmanians had "lost" the ability to make fire.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Tasmanian Aboriginal people extensively employed fire for cooking, warmth, tool hardening, and clearing vegetation to encourage and control macropod herds.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] This management may have caused the buttongrass plains in southwest Tasmania to develop to their current extent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Basket making is a traditional craft that has been developed into contemporary art.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Baskets had many uses, including carrying food, tools, shells, ochre, and eating utensils.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Basket-like carriers were made from plant materials, kelp, or animal skin.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The kelp baskets or carriers were used mainly to carry and serve water.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Plants were carefully selected to produce strong, thin, narrow strips of fibre of suitable length for basket making.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Several different species of plants were used, including white flag iris, blue flax lily, rush, and sag, some of which are still used by contemporary basket makers, and sometimes shells are added for ornament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Making necklaces from shells is a significant cultural tradition among Tasmanian Aboriginal women.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Necklaces were used for adornment, as gifts and tokens of honour, and as trading objects.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Dating back at least 2,600 years, necklace-making is one of the few Palawa traditions that has remained intact and has continued without interruption since before European settlement.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] A number of shell necklaces are held in the collection of the National Museum of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The necklaces were initially only made out of the shells of the *Phasianotrochus irisodontes* snail, commonly known as the rainbow kelp and usually referred to as maireener shells.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] There are three other species of maireeners found in Tasmanian waters.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] In the past 20 years, there has been a decline in the number of shells, since the decline in kelp and seaweed growth around Flinders Island, Cape Barren, and Big Dog islands due to climate change, which has led to erosion of the sea bed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Ochre is highly significant in Tasmanian Aboriginal culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Tasmanian ochre ranges in colour from white through yellow to red.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Its uses include ceremonial body marking, colouring wood craft products, tie-dyeing, and other crafts and arts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Traditionally, Aboriginal women had the exclusive role of obtaining ochre, and many Tasmanian Aboriginal men continue to respect this custom by obtaining ochre only from women.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Though ochre is mined from sites throughout Tasmania, the most celebrated source is Toolumbunner in the Gog Range of NW Tasmania, in the traditional lands of the Pallitorre clan.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] This was also a significant site of tribal meeting, celebration, and trading.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Colonial settlers describe various traditional Aboriginal Australian ceremonies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] One has been called "corobery", although that is a mainland Aboriginal word adopted by British settlers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Ceremonial dance and singing depicted traditional tales as well as recent events.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Robinson describes "horse-dance" depicting a horseman hunting an Aboriginal person, as well as the sensual "devil-dance" performed by women from the Furneaux Islands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Battles and funerals were also occasions for painting the body with ochre or black paint.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Contemporary colonial settlers cite several examples of pictorial art drawn on the insides of huts or on remnants of discarded paper.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] These designs are generally circular or spiral motifs that represent celestial bodies or figures of clan people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Robinson related that one design for an Aboriginal hut was very accurately drawn and created with a kind of wooden compass.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The most enduring art form left by Tasmanians are petroglyphs, or rock art.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The most elaborate site is at Preminghana on the West Coast, although other significant sites exist at the Bluff in Devonport and at Greenes Creek.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Smaller sites include the cupules at *meenamatta* Blue Tier and isolated circle motifs at Trial Harbour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Aboriginal people inhabited Tasmania's southwest from the last glacial maximum, and hand stencils and ochre smears are found in several caves, the oldest of which is dated to 10000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Tasmanian Aboriginal people are asserting their identity and culture through the visual arts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The art expresses the Aboriginal viewpoint on colonial history, race relations, and identity.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Themes consistent in modern Tasmanian Aboriginal art are loss, kinship, narratives of dispossession, but also survival.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The art is modern, using textiles, sculpture, and photography, but often incorporates ancient motifs and techniques such as shell necklaces and practical artifacts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Photographer Ricky Maynard has had his work exhibited internationally, and his documentary style "brings to light the stories of Aboriginal people where they have previously been absent or distorted.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Modern painting in Tasmania is starting to use techniques shared by Aboriginal art in mainland Australia but incorporating traditional Tasmanian motifs, such as spirals and celestial representations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] This shows that, like mainland Australia, Aboriginal art is dynamic and evolving from established post-colonial preconceptions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Tasmanian Aboriginal women have traditionally collected *Maireener* shells to fashion necklaces and bracelets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] This practice continues among Aboriginal women whose families survived on the Furneaux Islands, handed down by elder women to maintain an important link with the traditional lifestyle.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Late in the nineteenth century, a number of women sought to keep this part of their traditional culture alive so their daughters and granddaughters could participate in it.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Today, only a few Tasmanian Aboriginal women maintain this art, but they continue to pass down their knowledge and skills to younger women in their community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Shell necklace manufacture continues to maintain links with the past, expressed as a modern art form.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Tasmanian Aboriginal authors in the past century have written history, poetry, essays, and fiction.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Authors such as Ida West have written autobiographies recounting their experiences growing up within white society; Phyllis Pitchford, Errol West and Jim Everett have written poetry, while Everett and Greg Lehman have explored their tradition as essayists.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The Oyster Cove people attracted contemporaneous international scientific interest from the 1860s onwards, with many museums claiming body parts for their collections.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Scientists were interested in studying Aboriginal Tasmanians from a physical anthropology perspective, hoping to gain insights into the field of paleoanthropology.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] For these reasons, they were interested in individual Aboriginal body parts and whole skeletons.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Tasmanian Aboriginal skulls were particularly sought internationally for studies into craniofacial anthropometry.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Truganini herself feared that her body would be exploited after her death, and two years after she died, her body was exhumed and sent to Melbourne for scientific study.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Her skeleton was then put up for public display in the Tasmanian Museum until 1947, and was only laid to rest, by cremation, in 1976.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] However, many of these skeletons were obtained from Aboriginal "mummies" from graves or bodies of the murdered.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Amalie Dietrich, for example, became famous for delivering such specimens.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Aboriginal people have considered the dispersal of body parts as being disrespectful, as a common aspect within Aboriginal belief systems is that a soul can only be at rest when laid in its homeland.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Body parts and ornaments are still being returned from collections today, with the Royal College of Surgeons of England returning samples of Truganini's skin and hair (in 2002), and the British Museum returning ashes to two descendants in 2007.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] While no consensus exists as to the cause of the decimation of the Aboriginal Tasmanian population, many scholars consider the decimation to constitute a genocide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The debate about the cause generated a major controversy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The traditional view held that this dramatic demographic collapse was the result of the impact of introduced diseases, rather than the consequence of policy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Geoffrey Blainey, for example, wrote that by 1830 in Tasmania: "Disease had killed most of them but warfare and private violence had also been devastating." Keith Windschuttle claimed that in addition to disease, the prostitution of women in a society already in decline, explained the extinction.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Henry Reynolds attributed the depletion to losses in the Black War.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Many historians of colonialism and genocide, such as Ben Kiernan, Colin Tatz, and Benjamin Madley, consider that the Tasmanian decimation qualifies as genocide by the definition of Raphael Lemkin adopted in the UN Genocide Convention.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Lemkin himself considered Tasmania to be the site of one of the world's clear cases of genocide and Robert Hughes has described the loss of Aboriginal Tasmanians as "the only true genocide in English colonial history".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Other scholars who have supported the assessment of the near-destruction of the Aboriginal Tasmanians as genocide include James Boyce, Lyndall Ryan, Tom Lawson, Mohamed Adhikari, Ashley Riley Sousa, Rebe Taylor, and Tony Barta.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] In June 2005, the Tasmanian Legislative Council introduced a reformed definition of Aboriginality into the Aboriginal Lands Act.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The bill was passed to allow Aboriginal Lands Council elections to commence, resolving the uncertainty over who was "Aboriginal" and thus eligible to vote.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] There are many people currently working in the community, academia, various levels of government, and NGOs to strengthen Tasmanian Aboriginal culture and improve the conditions of the descendant community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] In November 2006, Tasmania became the first Australian state or territory to offer financial compensation for the Stolen Generations, Aboriginal people forcibly removed from their families by Australian government agencies and church missions between about 1900 and 1972.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] The **Stolen Generations of Aboriginal Children Act 2006** was passed unanimously by all members of the Tasmanian Parliament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aboriginal-tasmanians-p02] Up to 40 Aboriginal Tasmanians' descendants are expected to be eligible for compensation from the $5 million package.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] In grammar, the **absolutive case** (abbreviated **abs**) is the case of nouns in ergative–absolutive languages that would generally be the subjects of intransitive verbs or the objects of transitive verbs in the translational equivalents of nominative–accusative languages such as English.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] In languages with ergative–absolutive alignment, the absolutive is the case used to mark both the subject of an intransitive verb and the object of a transitive verb in addition to being used for the citation form of a noun.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] It contrasts with the marked ergative case, which marks the subject of a transitive verb.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] In a very few cases, a marked absolutive has been reported, including in Nias and Sochiapam Chinantec.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] Occasionally, the term 'absolutive case' (or also: 'absolute case') is used for the unmarked case form in languages with other alignment types.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] This is especially common in the tradition of descriptive linguistics of African languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] In marked nominative languages, where the nominative has case inflection, the accusative is unmarked and also serves as citation form.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] In these languages, the unmarked accusative/citation form is thus often called 'absolutive'.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] On the other hand, in certain nominative–accusative languages, it is the accusative which is explicitly marked for case, whereas the nominative is unmarked and serves as citation form.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] In such situations, the term 'absolutive' is occasionally used to describe the unmarked nominative/citation form.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] In tripartite languages, both the agent and object of a transitive clause have case forms, ergative and accusative, and the agent of an intransitive clause is the unmarked citation form.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/absolutive-case] It is occasionally called the intransitive case, but *absolutive* is also used and is perhaps more accurate since it is not limited to core agents of intransitive verbs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The **Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies** (**AIATSIS**), established as the **Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies** (**AIAS**) in 1964, is an independent Australian Government statutory authority.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] It is a collecting, publishing, and research institute and is considered to be Australia's premier resource for information about the cultures and societies of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The institute is a leader in ethical research and the handling of culturally sensitive material.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The collection at AIATSIS has been built through over 50 years of research and engagement with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities and is now a source of language and culture revitalisation, native title research, and Indigenous family and community history.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is located on Acton Peninsula in Canberra, Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In the late 1950s, there was an increasing focus on the global need for anthropological research into 'disappearing cultures'.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This trend was also emerging in Australia in the work of researchers of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, leading to a proposal by W.C.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Wentworth MP for the conception of an Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies (AIAS) in 1959.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The proposal was made as a submission to Cabinet, and argued for a more comprehensive approach by the Australian Government to the recording of Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples and cultures.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 1960, a Cabinet sub-committee assessed the proposal and formed a working party at the Australian National University (ANU) to consider the viability of the proposal.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] One of their first actions was to appoint W.E.H.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Stanner to organise a conference on the state of Aboriginal Studies in Australia, to be held in 1961 at the ANU.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Academics and anthropologists in the field of Aboriginal Studies attended the conference, and contributed research papers published in a conference report in 1963.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] No Aboriginal people were present at the conference.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Prime Minister at the time, Robert Menzies, appointed an Interim Council in 1961.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The role of the Interim Council was to plan for a national Aboriginal research organisation and establish how this organisation would interact with existing research and scientific bodies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Interim Council was also tasked with immediately developing a programme that would identify and address urgent research needs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Interim Council consisted of 16 members and was chaired by Deputy Vice-Chancellor of the ANU, Professor A.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Trendall, officially recognised as the first chair of the institute now known as AIATSIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In August 1962, a draft constitution for the institute was submitted to the Menzies government, and rejected.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Interim Council completed a revised constitution in July 1963.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Amendments to the document included the change from the title 'director' to 'principal' of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This version of the constitution would go on to form the basis for the creation of the new Australian Institute for Aboriginal Studies the following year.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies was established as a statutory authority under an Act of Parliament in June 1964.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The mission of the Institute at that time has been described as "to record language, song, art, material culture, ceremonial life and social structure before those traditions perished in the face of European ways".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This notion is also reflected in the Institute's official functions, as recorded in the Reading of the Bill in Parliament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] 2. to treat as a matter of urgency those studies for which the source materials are disappearing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] 3. to establish and conduct a documentation centre on the Aborigines, and a library of books, manuscripts and other relevant material, both for the use of scholars and for public education.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] 4. to encourage co-operation with and between scholars in universities, museums, and other institutions engaged in studies of the Aborigines, and with appropriate private bodies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] 5. to publish and to support the publication of the results of research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] 6. to co-operate with appropriate bodies concerning the financing of research, the preservation of sites, and the collection of records.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] 7. to promote as and when necessary the training of research workers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] 8. to establish and maintain relations with relevant international bodies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIAS had a twenty-two member Council, composed mainly of academics, and had a foundation membership of one hundred.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The founding Principal of the newly formed institute was Frederick McCarthy, a professional anthropologist and graduate of Sydney University who had spent nearly 30 years working in the field.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The creation of the AIAS provided an opportunity for greater cross-discipline interaction in fields relating to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander studies in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Institute's founding principal, Fred McCarthy, was an advocate of film as an important part of research methodology as early as his tenure as curator of anthropology at the Australian Museum in Sydney in the 1940s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This was evident in the contributions he made during his involvement in establishing the AIAS and also as its principal, in continuing to support the development of the AIAS Film Unit and championing ethnographic film in global forums.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In the early years of the AIAS, the Film Unit largely outsourced early filmmaking work to other companies, or worked in collaboration with the Commonwealth Film Unit (as early as 1962).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] But over the next 30 years, the Film Unit would go on to produce "one of the largest assembly of ethnographic films created in the world".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In keeping with the AIAS official function "to publish and to support the publication of the results of research", a publishing arm of the institute was established in 1964.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Publishing under the name Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies, the publishing arm released a range of papers and research findings, including in the fields of linguistics, demography, physical anthropology, history and musicology.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The early work of the AIAS is credited with increasing interaction between academics in different fields, as well as establishing the foundations for the extensive collections AIATSIS holds today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] But before 1970, there had never been an Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander member on the AIAS Council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The 1970s marked a period of change for the AIAS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This began with the appointment of the first Aboriginal member of the AIAS Council in 1970.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Phillip Roberts, an Alawa man, served on the council from September 1970 until June 1972.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This was followed in 1971 with a second Aboriginal Council member, Senator Neville Bonner, who served on Council until 1974 and for a second term in the late 1970s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] And again in 1972, with the appointment of Dick Roughsey to replace Phillip Roberts at the end of his term.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The appointment of Phillip Roberts to the Council reflected a growing pressure for an increase in Aboriginal representation within the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] But the move did not allay the belief held by some Aboriginal activists that the AIAS was engaging in 'tokenism' in the extent to which Aboriginal people were involved in the administration of Aboriginal Studies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The changes to the Institute that would take place in the following decade were also influenced by the shifting social and political landscape in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal rights movement was growing and Aboriginal people were demanding a voice on Council, consultation with communities and an increased focus on projects relevant to the needs of Indigenous people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 1972, the Whitlam government was elected.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Their policy of self-determination for Aboriginal people echoed calls for greater Aboriginal involvement in the administration and functions of the AIAS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The new government was also responsible for a significant boost to AIAS funding.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The appointment of Peter Ucko in 1972 as Principal of the AIAS has since been described as the beginning of an increase in involvement of Aboriginal people in the workings of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In his time as Principal, Ucko was responsible for implementing a policy later labelled "Aboriginalisation", which was aimed at opening up the institute to Aboriginal involvement and representation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This policy was influenced by a document circulated in 1974, called the Eaglehawk and Crow letter, which criticised the current model of academic research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The policy and structural changes to the Institute continued throughout the 1970s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal Advisory Committee was established in 1975, and consisted of the six Aboriginal members of the AIAS Council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Early recommendations including increased representation of Aboriginal people on committees and the AIAS Council as well as employment at the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The committee was renamed in 1978, to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Advisory Committee.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 1975–1976, a category of research grants for Aboriginal researchers was introduced.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The emergence of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people filling the role of 'cultural practitioner', travelling to the AIAS to provide advice on projects and research being undertaken, was also documented from around 1976 onwards.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The time Peter Ucko spent as Principal of the AIAS saw a phase of "rapid expansion" for the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The AIAS Film Unit that had operated in Sydney until 1973 was re-established in Canberra in 1975.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Prominent American-born ethnographic filmmaker David MacDougall was appointed the Director of this new AIAS Film Unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] With his wife and filmmaking partner Judith MacDougall and Kim McKenzie, the Film Unit operated until 1988 when its functions were absorbed back into the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] During the MacDougall/McKenzie era, a new style of ethnographic film was explored.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] One that moved away from film as a scientific record in favour of telling the story of individuals lives.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The filmmakers also practised a more collaborative approach to their films, and chose to use translations and subtitles to give direct access to the subjects voice and thoughts rather than the dominant 'voice of god' narration style.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] One of the most notable films produced towards the end of this period was *Waiting for Harry*, a prize-winning film directed by Kim McKenzie with anthropologist Les Hiatt and now considered to exemplify the "style of collaborative filmmaking" the Film Unit favoured in their work.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The power of film to "influence opinion" was becoming increasingly recognised and with this, the lack of representation of Aboriginal people telling their own stories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 1978, a meeting chaired by prominent activist and academic Marcia Langton expressed these concerns, arguing for greater access to film and video in Aboriginal communities, and training in film production by the AIAS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] By the following year, the AIAS Film Unit had begun to implement a training program and had started employing trainee Aboriginal filmmakers on productions by the early 1980s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The AIAS began presenting a biennial Wentworth Lecture in 1978, named as a tribute to W.C.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Wentworth for his role in establishing the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The lecture is presented by prominent person with knowledge or experience relating to issues affecting Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples in Australia today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The expansion of the Institute continued into the 1980s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal Studies Press began publishing the Australian Aboriginal Studies Journal in 1983, a peer-reviewed journal aimed at "promoting high-quality research in Australian Indigenous studies".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 1982, the AIAS established a task force that identified the prevailing need for further 'Aboriginalisation' of the Institute's workforce.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] At the time, there were four Aboriginal staff members, making up around 7% of the total staff.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This was followed in 1985 with the creation of the role of Aboriginal Studies Coordination Officer within the AIAS, whose responsibilities involved improving access for Aboriginal people to the research and resources of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The *After 200 Years* project was launched in 1985, aiming to fill some of the gaps in the AIAS photographic collection; particularly images of daily life in the southern, urban parts of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Aboriginal involvement in selecting subject matter, photographing and documenting the collection was a major part of the project.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The three-year project culminated in the publication of a book containing hundreds of photographs of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, and selected by them to represent their community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Rock Art Protection Program (RAPP) commenced in 1986 following a request for such an initiative by the then Minister of Aboriginal Affairs Clyde Holding.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The aim of the RAPP was to protect Australian Indigenous rock art.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Grants were approved by the institute to fund various projects related to rock art protection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The collections were also expanding, and by 1987 the AIATSIS library encompassed the print collections, a special Bibliographic Section and the Resource Centre (which contained the Institute's audiovisual materials).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Between 1987 and 1989, the survival of the AIAS as an independent statutory body was tied to a proposal for a new statutory commission that would take over all aspects of the Aboriginal Affairs portfolio.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This commission would become the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC), conceived in an Act of Parliament in 1989.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The AIAS would not be folded into this commission; instead it would be recreated under a new Act with a new name.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The *Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies (AIATSIS) Act* was passed by parliament in 1989, replacing the AIAS Act.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The newly established AIATSIS had a reduced Council consisting of nine members, with the AIATSIS Act specifying that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people hold a minimum of five of these Council positions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The new Act also established a Research Advisory Committee, to assess research applications and advise the council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal Studies Press published their best-selling Aboriginal Australia map in 1996, based on research conducted for the Encyclopaedia of Aboriginal Australia, edited by David Horton.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 2001, the Institute launched a two-year Library Digitisation Pilot Program (LDPP).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Among the items digitised, catalogued and made available online were 267 volumes of the *Dawn* and *New Dawn* magazines held in the AIATSIS collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS also distributed over 2000 free copies of these magazines on CD-Rom, to Indigenous organisations, schools and libraries in New South Wales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Throughout this period, AIATSIS continued to undertake projects focused on the digitisation of collection materials, including their holdings of the complete back catalogue of *Koori Mail*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This involved scanning over 35,000 pages from 500 editions of the newspaper, with searchable copies launched on the AIATSIS website in partnership with Koori Mail in 2011.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] As part of their research functions, AIATSIS also initiated a number of public programs and research related events during this time that are still run today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The institute has convened the National Indigenous Studies Conference every two years since 2001 and the National Native Title Conference every year since 2002.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The *After 200 Years* photographic project was revisited in 2014 with an exhibition of images at Parliament House, Canberra, to coincide with AIATSIS' 50-year anniversary.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 2020, following consultation with the United Ngunnawal Elders Council and the Winanggaay Ngunnawal Language Group, the AIATSIS building in Acton was officially named *Maraga*, which means a strong shield.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] On 2 February 2024, coinciding with its 60th anniversary, AIATSIS opened a new facility in Mparntwe-Alice Springs, building on its long partnership with First Nations Media Australia, which is based in the city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS staff, six of whom are Indigenous locals (of seven in total; intended to grow to up to 24) located at the new centre will work closely with local people to take care of the cultural heritage from the region.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] There is a dedicated ancestry section in the new centre, which before its completion was referred to as AIATSIS Alice Springs Engagement and Digitisation Centre and is now officially known as AIATSIS Central Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The centre will be run in collaboration with the Northern Territory Government, and allow access to AIATSIS materials for people living in Central Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] An exhibition titled *To Know, To Respect, To Care* is on at the centre until 14 June 2024.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The official opening was attended by Linda Burney, the Minister for Indigenous Australians, and NT Minister for Arts, Culture and Heritage Chansey Paech.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is an Australian Government statutory authority established under the *Public Governance, Performance and Accountability Act 2013*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] As of 2024 it is under the portfolio of the Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet, and Hon Linda Burney, Minister for Indigenous Australians, is the responsible minister.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] 6. to encourage understanding, in the general community, of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander societies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The AIATSIS Council is a governing body designed to oversee and steer the functions and direction of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The role and responsibilities of the council are mandated in the *AIATSIS Act 1989*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Council consists of nine members; four are elected by the institute's membership and five appointed by the Minister.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] According to the AIATSIS Act 1989, one person appointed by the Minister must be a Torres Strait Islander and the four other people appointed by the Minister must be Aboriginal persons or Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The four Council members elected by the Institute's membership must be members themselves.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Various advisory committees exist to assist the Council as well as the chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Indigenous Caucus is a working group providing a forum for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander staff to meet and discuss workplace issues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Indigenous Caucus was revitalised in 2003–2004 and contributed to the development of policies and procedures in that year, notably AIATSIS' Indigenous Training and Career Development Plan.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 2013, the Indigenous Caucus developed a formal Service Charter and elected an Executive consisting of three members.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Native Title Research Advisory Committee (NTRAC) provides advice to the CEO on the research program of the Native Title Research Unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Research Advisory Committee (RAC) is responsible for assessing and advising on AIATSIS research projects and programs, including research grants.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] RAC functions are established in the AIATSIS Act.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Research Ethics Committee (REC) is responsible for advising AIATSIS on the ethics of the research proposals by staff or grantees of AIATSIS, as well as research carried out through the Institute's external collaborations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The roles in the Research Ethics Committee are based on the National Statement published by the National Health and Medical Research Council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The AIATSIS Act sets the organisation the task of conducting, facilitating and promoting research in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies and training Indigenous researchers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] For over 50 years, AIATSIS has conducted research across a range of areas of study relevant to Indigenous peoples, culture, heritage, knowledge and experiences.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This has led to a diverse research history; from languages and archaeological research, land rights, and political engagement, to contemporary topics in health and commerce.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The AIATSIS collections not only contain priceless records of Australia's Indigenous cultural heritage, but provide a significant national and international research infrastructure for research by, for and about Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is one of Australia's Publicly Funded Research Agencies (PFRA), alongside organisations such as CSIRO and the Australian Institute of Marine Science.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is Australia's only non-science PFRA.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Currently AIATSIS undertakes research in six priority areas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The institute is a leader in ethical research and the handling of culturally sensitive material. and holds in its collections many unique and irreplaceable items of cultural, historical and spiritual significance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS published the *Guidelines for Ethical Research in Australian Indigenous Studies* (referred to as GERAIS) in 1999.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This was a document considered to be the leading ethics guidelines for conducting research in and with Indigenous communities in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] GERAIS was regularly revised and significantly updated in 2012.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] GERAIS was replaced in 2020 by *AIATSIS Code of Ethics for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Research (the AIATSIS Code)*, which supersedes GERAIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Accompanying it is "A Guide to applying The AIATSIS Code of Ethics for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Research".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 2013, AIATSIS was involved in the review of two National Health and Medical Research Council research ethics guidelines relating to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS began undertaking native title research activities through the Native Title Research Unit in 1993, following the 1992 *Mabo v Queensland* High Court decision.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Native Title Research Advisory Committee, the Research Advisory Committee, and the AIATSIS Council oversee the work conducted in Native Title and traditional ownership research at AIATSIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS conducts a range of research projects relating to Native Title and traditional ownership, including Native Title and cultural heritage, Native Title and fresh and sea water, and Prescribed Body Corporates.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The role of Native Title research at AIATSIS is to monitor outcomes of Native Title and through research and study, provide advice on Native Title policy development.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Institute publishes a range of materials relating to Native Title including books, discussion papers, research reports and a Native Title Newsletter.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS also provides a Native Title Research and Access Officer, who is responsible for assisting Native Title claimants to access materials from the AIATSIS collections in support of their claim.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Up until 2019, AIATSIS also contributed to Native Title policy and research by co-organising the Annual National Native Title Conference.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] However, in 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic in Australia, the conference was cancelled, and in 2021 it merged with the National Indigenous Research Conference, creating a five-day event known as the AIATSIS Summit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS publishes a number of resources for anyone wishing to undertake research into their own family history.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The *Family History kit* is aimed at providing the basics for tracing Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander heritage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] It contains guides to AIATSIS' own resources, including the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Biographical Index (ABI) and digitised collection materials, as well as guides to external resources that may help with family history research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] General guidance is also provided regarding research resources specific to Indigenous family history research, historical name conventions and usage and confirmation of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander heritage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS also provides research support to Link-Up case workers and researchers around Australia, who are assisting members of the Stolen Generations to reconnect with their family and heritage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In keeping with its mandated functions, AIATSIS publishes the results of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies through their publishing arm, Aboriginal Studies Press (ASP).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Institute began publishing in 1962 with *A demographic survey of the Aboriginal population of the Northern Territory, with special reference to Bathurst Island Mission*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] This and other early publications were released under the imprint Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies, the former title of AIATSIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The ASP publishing imprint was trademarked in 2002, but was operating as the publishing arm of AIATSIS as early as the publication of Helen Ross' *Just For Living* in 1987.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The **AIATSIS Research Publications** became an imprint in 2011 and its stated purpose is to publish scholarly research that is derived from the AIATSIS Research Program.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] All Aboriginal Studies Press-branded titles are peer-reviewed and the majority are published concurrently in print and several ebook formats.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The first phone app was published in 2013, and was shortlisted for the 2013 Mobile Awards.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Titles published by ASP have included research reports, monographs, biographies, autobiographies, family and community histories, and children's books.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Since 2005 the list has aligned more closely with the Institute's research focus.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Most publications derive from academic research, some funded by AIATSIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] ASP publishes books by both Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander and non-Indigenous authors who are writing in the field of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In some cases Aboriginal authors, like Doreen Kartinyeri and Joan Martin, have chosen to write in collaboration with non-Aboriginal oral historians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Publishing Advisory Committee makes recommendations to the AIATSIS Principal and Aboriginal Studies Press about which manuscripts to publish from those submitted.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] It has relationships with distributors and resellers for both national and international print and ebook distribution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Another widely used resource published by Aboriginal Studies Press is the **Aboriginal Australia map**, created by David Horton.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal Australia map represents the general locations of larger groupings of Aboriginal people, using research that was conducted during the development of *The Encyclopaedia of Aboriginal Australia*, which was another significant ASP publication.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Previous milestone publications included the book *After 200 Years*, a collaboration showcasing photographs and stories of Aboriginal people as selected by members of those communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Both books are now out of print and only available in libraries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] ASP also publishes the Stanner Award winner for a scholarly manuscript (not fiction or poetry) by an Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander, which recognises the importance of being published to emerging academics.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The prize includes mentoring and editorial support by ASP, as well as publication of the manuscript, A$5,000, and a glass sculpture by Jenni Kemarre Martiniello.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The biennial award is named in honour of the anthropologist W.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] (Bill) Stanner, who played an important role in establishing the AIAS, and the ongoing development of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] In 1996, *Auntie Rita*, a biography of Rita Huggins co-written by her and her daughter Jackie Huggins, won the award.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] Anna Haebich won the 1999 award for her work *Broken circles: Fragmenting indigenous families 1800–2000*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The 2011 award was won by human rights advocate and lawyer Hannah McGlade in 2011.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The AIATSIS website hosts the **AUSTLANG** database, an informative source of information on all known Aboriginal Australian languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] With its beginnings on a card file compiled in the 1990s, the Indigenous Languages Database (ILDB) was developed based on the Language Thesaurus maintained by the AIATSIS library since the 1960s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The online version of AUSTLANG was developed in 2005, revised and released to the public in 2008, and after more redevelopment work, a refined version was released in 2018.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS hosts a range of special events and research workshops, symposiums and conferences.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is located on the Acton Peninsula in a building that was newly built for the Institute and opened in 2001.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The building was officially opened by the Honourable W.C.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] As part of the opening the Ngunnawal people, the traditional owners of the land on which the AIATSIS building stands performed a Welcome to Country and smoking ceremony, and the Anbarra people from North Central Arnhem Land performed a friendship ceremony, known as the Rom ceremony.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The architect, Howard Ragatt of the firm Ashton Raggatt McDougall designed the building for AIATSIS and for its neighbour on the Acton Peninsula, the National Museum of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] During design of the AIATSIS building, it was reoriented from original plans to save two apple box trees that were identified as significant to the Peninsula.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The building cost $13.75 million and was funded by the Commonwealth Government's Centenary of Federation Grants Program.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The design of the AIATSIS building has been the subject of differing interpretations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The rear of the building has been described as a black copy of pioneer architect Le Corbusier's 1920s Villa Savoye in France.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The architect, Howard Raggatt, was quoted as confirming this influence but has also stated that it is designed to be reminiscent of Sidney Nolan's famous paintings of Ned Kelly.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] A new building is planned in Canberra, to be located in a precinct to be named Ngurra, on the shores of Lake Burley Griffin, in the Parliamentary Triangle.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The new precinct A$316.5 million will also include a new centre for learning and knowledge, and a resting place for ancestral remains of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from around the nation who are unable to be located in their Country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The name *Ngurra* occurs in several Aboriginal languages, meaning "home", "camp", "a place of belonging or inclusion".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] A design competition was held in 2022 to select the architects for the project.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] A new AIATSIS facility known as AIATSIS Central Australia was opened on 2 February 2024 in Alice Springs/Mparntwe, to serve Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people in Central Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p01] The offices and exhibition spaces were created from two vacant retail premises in Todd Mall.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS is considered to be Australia's premier resource for information about the cultures and societies of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS is the only Commonwealth of Australia institution responsible for collecting and maintaining materials documenting the oral and visual traditions and histories of Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The Institute identifies its collection as a "keeping place for culturally significant objects" that is "a resource for anybody looking to improve their knowledge of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander history and culture".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The institute's holdings represent thousands of years of history and more than 500 Australian Indigenous languages, dialects and groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] This collection supports, and is a result of, research in the fields of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] An independent assessment in 2014 confirmed that AIATSIS holds over 6 million feet of film, over 40,000 hours of audio, 12,800 unpublished manuscripts and record series, 653,000 photographs, and 120,000 print and published materials (3,000 of which are rare books) among other miscellanea.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] As of 2024 it was estimated that it holds over a million cultural items, which include 42,000 hours of audio, over 700,000 photographs, and around 6 million feet of film.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The Audiovisual Archives also holds copies of the first audio recorded in Australia; a series of ethnographic wax cylinder recordings made in the Torres Strait Islands in 1898.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The Cambridge Anthropological Expedition to the Torres Strait, led by Alfred Cort Haddon, recorded songs and speech from Mer/Murray Island, Mabuiag/Jervis Island, Saibai Island, Tudu Island and Iama/Yam Island.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Since the establishment of the Institute in 1964, the AIATSIS collection has been developed through acquisition by donation, gift and purchase or, through materials created and collected during the work of ethnographic field researchers and filmmakers funded by the AIATSIS grants program.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The collection has also been built through deposits of materials, an arrangement which permits the original owners to assign access and use conditions appropriate to the cultural information contained in the items.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Once material has been acquired by AIATSIS, the Institute faces the challenges of maintaining a cultural resource collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] This is achieved through a collection management plan that involves processes of recording and cataloguing, and appropriate storage and handling to extend the life of physical items and preserving their content through format shifting.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Storage of collection items in climate-controlled vaults, to maintain their integrity and to minimise contact with deteriorating agents such as moisture and light.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The Institute also follows international archiving guidelines for the storage and preservation of materials.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] There are a wide variety of analogue photograph, tape and film formats held in the AIATSIS collection, which pose special preservation and future access risks.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The age of some of these formats and materials, combined with the varying conditions in which they were stored prior to their acquisition by AIATSIS, heightens the deterioration of the media.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Another preservation issue inherent in these analogue materials is the machines that can play back that particular format, as in some cases the material and the playback device are no longer manufactured.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] To manage these risks and maintain future access to the collection, preservation of the actual content contained in collection items is also achieved through a program of digitisation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Due to the potential issues of long-term archiving and storage of digital items, the opposite process is often employed to ensure access and preservation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] In the case of digital publications and manuscripts, the originals will often be printed and incorporated into the print collections as an additional preservation measure.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The AIATSIS collection holds material that is sensitive and/or secret/sacred to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] In accordance with its founding Act, and as part of their collection management plan, AIATSIS adheres to strict protocols when handling and processing these sensitive items.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The institute also supports and adheres to the protocols developed by the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Library, Information and Resource Network (ATSILIRN).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Restricted visual media such as photographs and printed items are stored separately to the rest of the collection and audio and moving image items are not played until any cultural requirements are checked.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Restricted material must also be carefully handled during digitisation, which means that the work is carried out in secured conditions such as enclosed booths and by staff that can meet the protocols of the item being digitised.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS launched its Library Digitisation Pilot Program in 2001, before which the Library had no dedicated digitisation equipment or policies for managing digital materials.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] This two-year program was originally funded by the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC), and involved the creation of digital collections across the institution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Since then AIATSIS has continued to incorporate digitisation of the collection into its management plan, but have publicly stated that an increase in funding is required for the institute to digitise some of the at risk formats held in the collection before those items are lost.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Given these limitations, AIATSIS prioritises the selection of materials for digitisation using factors including significance of the item/s, the level of deterioration, cultural protocols, copyright status, and client demand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] One of the identified priorities of the program is to digitise and preserve all of the audiovisual collection currently on endangered magnetic tape formats by the 2025 deadline set by UNESCO.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The collection is housed in the AIATSIS building on Acton Peninsula and is accessible through a number of resources.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The AIATSIS Library is open to the public and holds a range of printed materials including manuscripts, journals, readers in different Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander languages, dictionaries, published books and rare books, maps, and posters.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Access to AIATSIS' print and manuscript collections can be made through the Library's Stanner Reading Room and the film, sound and pictorial collections by appointment through the Access Unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] These physical access points are open limited hours.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The AIATSIS Digitisation Program contributes to increased access to the collection; whether access is through on site resources, the provision of copies of materials or the sharing of the collection online.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Due to increasing obsolescence of analogue formats, AIATSIS identifies digitisation as the way to preserve those items for future generations to access.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] This is considered to be particularly important for facilitating "remote access by Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities" as well as for access by researchers and the general public.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The AIATSIS Access Unit runs a program called Return of Material to Indigenous Communities (ROMTIC), through which Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander clients are provided with up to twenty copies of collection materials that relate to their language group or family.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] This service is limited to items that have been preserved, so AIATSIS' digitisation program has allowed an increasing number of digital items available to ROMTIC clients.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS also makes the collection available through a series of online exhibitions and digitised collection material published on their website.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Access to the AIATSIS collection is also dictated by legislation governing the Institute and in some instances by legal agreements outlining the terms under which collection materials can be used.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The terms for access to the AIATSIS collection are in the first instance set by the AIATSIS Act, Section 41.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The conditions referred to in Section 41(1) of the AIATSIS Act are usually covered in the agreement that AIATSIS enters into when material is deposited.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] These agreements, along with the section 41(2) of the Act, can govern the way that unpublished material can be accessed and used.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Access to and use of material in the AIATSIS collection is also subject to the terms set out in the Copyright Act (1968).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] When a donation or deposit is being made, AIATSIS requests to be made aware of any sensitive items included in the material.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The secret or sacred nature of information contained in many collection items is an important factor in access to the AIATSIS collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] In response to these complex issues AIATSIS developed an overarching Access and Use Policy in 2014, to "manage legal and cultural rights over material while maximising accessibility".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] Since its inception, AIATSIS has developed and maintained a range of resources to enhance discoverability of the collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] One of the most significant of these resources is the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Biographical Index (ABI).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The ABI had its beginnings in 1979 as a non-selective biographical register of names, constructed using information on Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from published material in the collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] In the early years of the biographical register, it was hoped it could "provide an important record of the achievements of Aboriginal people, and be a source of pride for generations to come".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] The former Perfect Pictures Database appears to have been superseded by the Photographic Collection, which contains around 400,000 (and growing) digitised images, and more than 700,000 images in total.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] For copyright and cultural reasons, the images may only be viewed in the Stanner Reading Room, but caption information is available online, and copies of the images may be requested.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS also hosts or contributes to other online resources, aimed at facilitating access to and understanding of the collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Australian languages have historically been classified into numerous language families.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Despite the diversity of Australian languages, many linguists have considered for decades that most languages of the Australian continent, including Pama-Nyungan, are members of one higher-level family.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] A proto-language, Proto-Australian, was reconstructed for the first time in 2024.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Proto-Australian is dated to approximately 6,000 years before the present, much later than human habitation of Australia; how it spread across the continent, replacing earlier languages, is as yet unclear.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] There have always been some Australian languages excluded from larger groupings as language isolates; currently, Tiwi and the Tasmanian languages are considered unrelated to Proto-Australian.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Of the languages of the Torres Strait, Kala Lagaw Ya is a Pama-Nyungan language, while Meriam Mer is a Papuan language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] At the start of the 21st century, fewer than 150 Aboriginal languages remained in daily use, with the majority being highly endangered.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In 2020, 90 percent of the barely more than 100 languages still spoken are considered endangered.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Thirteen languages are still being acquired by children.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The surviving languages are located in the most isolated areas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Of the five least endangered Western Australian Aboriginal languages, four belong to the Western Desert grouping of the Central and Great Victoria Desert.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In 2026 the most widely-spoken languages by Australian Aboriginal people are those whose origins post-date the colonisation of Australia; these languages include Australian Kriol, Australian Aboriginal English, and Light Warlpiri.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The Indigenous languages of Australia number in the hundreds, the precise number being quite uncertain, although there is a range of estimates from a minimum of around 250 up to possibly 363.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In 2020, 90 per cent of the barely more than 100 languages still spoken are considered endangered.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Yolŋu languages from north-east Arnhem Land are also currently learned by children.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Bilingual education is being used successfully in some communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Seven of the most widely spoken Australian languages, such as Warlpiri, Murrinh-patha and Tiwi, retain between 1,000 and 3,000 speakers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Some Indigenous communities and linguists show support for learning programmes either for language revival proper or for only "post-vernacular maintenance" (Indigenous communities having the opportunity to learn some words and concepts related to the lost language).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The *National Indigenous Languages Survey* is a regular Australia-wide survey of the status of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander languages conducted in 2005, 2014 and 2019.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Total 47 languages, 42,300 speakers, with 11 having only approximately 100.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Most Australian languages are commonly held to belong to the Pama–Nyungan family, a family accepted by most linguists, with Robert M.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] For convenience, the rest of the languages, all spoken in the far north, are commonly lumped together as "Non-Pama–Nyungan", although this does not necessarily imply that they constitute a valid clade.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Dixon argues that after perhaps 40,000 years of mutual influence and only a few centuries of written records, it is no longer possible to distinguish deep genealogical relationships from areal features in Australia, and that not even Pama–Nyungan is a valid language family.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] However, few other linguists accept Dixon's thesis.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Hale describes Dixon's scepticism as an erroneous phylogenetic assessment which is "such an insult to the eminently successful practitioners of Comparative Method Linguistics in Australia, that it positively demands a decisive riposte".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Johanna Nichols suggests that the northern families may be relatively recent arrivals from Maritime Southeast Asia, perhaps later replaced there by the spread of Austronesian.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] That could explain the typological difference between Pama–Nyungan and non-Pama–Nyungan languages, but not how a single family came to be so widespread.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Nicholas Evans suggests that the Pama–Nyungan family spread along with the now-dominant Aboriginal culture that includes the Australian Aboriginal kinship system.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] This Proto-Australian language, they concluded, would have been spoken about 12,000 years ago in northern Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In 2024, Harvey and Mailhammer published a book-length reconstruction of Proto-Australian.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] For a long time unsuccessful attempts were made to detect a link between Australian and Papuan languages, the latter being represented by those spoken on the coastal areas of New Guinea facing the Torres Strait and the Arafura Sea.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Foley noted lexical similarities between Robert M.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Dixon's 1980 reconstruction of proto-Australian and the East New Guinea Highlands languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Dixon, in the meantime, later abandoned his proto-Australian proposal.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] According to Claire Bowern's *Australian Languages* (2011), Australian languages divide into approximately 30 primary sub-groups and 5 isolates.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In 1962, Arthur Capell gave his assessment of the origins and internal grouping of Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] He referred to many attempts having been made to link the Australian languages to other parts of the world, including the Dravidian languages of South India, those of the Andaman Islands, and African languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Unclassified groups occupying the bulk of Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In 1967 Carl Georg von Brandenstein claimed that he had isolated and identified some sixty Portuguese language loanwords in several indigenous languages of Australia's far north.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Australian linguists have generally dismissed these conclusions, except perhaps for the word *tartaruga*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Nick Thieberger, a Melbourne University linguist, argues that Brandenstein's approach was still strongly influenced by outdated nineteenth-century linguistic thinking.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] It has been inferred from the probable number of languages and the estimate of pre-contact population levels that there may have been from 3,000 to 4,000 speakers on average for each of the 250 languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] A number of these languages were almost immediately wiped out within decades of colonisation, the case of the Aboriginal Tasmanians being a notorious example.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Tasmania had been separated from the mainland at the end of the Quaternary glaciation, and Indigenous Tasmanians remained isolated from the outside world for around 12,000 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Claire Bowern has concluded in a recent study that there were twelve Tasmanian languages, and that those languages are unrelated (that is, not demonstrably related) to those on the Australian mainland.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In 1990 it was estimated that 90 languages still survived of the approximately 250 once spoken, but with a high rate of attrition as elders died out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Of the 90, 70% by 2001 were judged as 'severely endangered' with only 17 spoken by all age groups, a definition of a 'strong' language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] On these grounds it is anticipated that despite efforts at linguistic preservation, many of the remaining languages will disappear within the next generation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The overall trend suggests that in the not too distant future all of the Indigenous languages will be lost, perhaps by 2050, and with them the cultural knowledge they convey.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] During the period of the Stolen Generations, Aboriginal children were removed from their families and placed in institutions where they were punished for speaking their Indigenous language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Different, mutually unintelligible language groups were often mixed together, with Australian Aboriginal English or Australian Kriol language as the only lingua franca.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The result was a disruption to the inter-generational transmission of these languages that severely impacted their future use.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Today, that same transmission of language between parents and grandparents to their children is a key mechanism for reversing language shift.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] There is some evidence to suggest that the reversal of the Indigenous language shift may lead to decreased self-harm and suicide rates among Indigenous youth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Nya jawgar yaam Gumbayynggir.*" (Translation: My father is Dhunghutti.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] And, therefore, I am Gumbayynggir.) In the House of Representatives on 31 August 2016 Linda Burney gave an acknowledgment of country in Wiradjuri in her first speech and was sung in by Lynette Riley in Wiradjuri from the public gallery.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] 2019 was the International Year of Indigenous Languages (IYIL2019), as declared by the United Nations General Assembly.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The commemoration was used to raise awareness of and support for the preservation of Aboriginal languages within Australia, including spreading knowledge about the importance of each language to the identity and knowledge of Indigenous groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Warrgamay/Girramay man Troy Wyles-Whelan joined the North Queensland Regional Aboriginal Corporation Language Centre (NQRACLC) in 2008, and has been contributing oral histories and the results of his own research to their database.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] As part of the efforts to raise awareness of the Wiradjuri language, a *Grammar of Wiradjuri language* was published in 2014 and *A new Wiradjuri dictionary* in 2010.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The New South Wales *Aboriginal Languages Act 2017* became law on 24 October 2017 and established a board to advise on the preservation of Aboriginal languages that is known as the Aboriginal Languages Trust.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] It was the first legislation in Australia to acknowledge the significance of first languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In 2019 the Royal Australian Mint issued a 50-cent coin to celebrate the International Year of Indigenous Languages which features 14 different words for "money" from Australian Indigenous languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The coin was designed by Aleksandra Stokic in consultation with Indigenous language custodian groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The work of digitising and transcribing many word lists created by ethnographer Daisy Bates in the 1900s at Daisy Bates Online provides a valuable resource for those researching especially Western Australian languages, and some languages of the Northern Territory and South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The project is co-ordinated by Nick Thieberger, who works in collaboration with the National Library of Australia "to have all the microfilmed images from Section XII of the Bates papers digitised".
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The project is succeeded by the Nyingarn Project , which digitises manuscripts and crowdsources transcriptions through DigiVol.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In recent decades, there have been attempts to revive indigenous languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Significant challenges exist, however, for the revival of languages in the dominant English language culture of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The Kaurna language, spoken by the Kaurna people of the Adelaide plains, has been the subject of a concerted revival movement since the 1980s, coordinated by Kaurna Warra Pintyanthi, a unit working out of the University of Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The language had rapidly disappeared after the settlement of South Australia and the breaking up of local indigenous people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Ivaritji, the last known speaker of the language, died in 1931.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] However, a substantial number of primary source records existed for the language, from which the language was reconstructed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The Tasmanian Aboriginal Centre, in collaboration with the University of Tasmania and the wider Aboriginal community, is undergoing the process of reviving Traditional Tasmanian languages through the construction of *palawa kani* (trans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The *palawa kani* Language Program has been in the works since the early 1990s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Due to the linguistic ethnocide of Aboriginal Tasmanians, *palawa kani* is the only Aboriginal language of Lutruwita/Tasmania today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] "Some Aboriginal people distinguish between *usership* and *ownership*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Whether it is due to genetic unity or some other factor such as occasional contact, typologically the Australian languages form a language area or *Sprachbund*, sharing much of their vocabulary and many distinctive phonological features across the entire continent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] A common feature of many Australian languages is that they display so-called avoidance speech, special speech registers used only in the presence of certain close relatives.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] These registers share the phonology and grammar of the standard language, but the lexicon is different and usually very restricted.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] There are also commonly speech taboos during extended periods of mourning or initiation that have led to numerous Aboriginal sign languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] For morphosyntactic alignment, many Australian languages have ergative–absolutive case systems.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] These are typically split systems; a widespread pattern is for pronouns (or first and second persons) to have nominative–accusative case marking and for third person to be ergative–absolutive, though splits between animate and inanimate are also found.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In some languages the persons in between the accusative and ergative inflections (such as second person, or third-person human) may be tripartite: that is, marked overtly as either ergative or accusative in transitive clauses, but not marked as either in intransitive clauses.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] There are also a few languages which employ only nominative–accusative case marking.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The following represents a canonical 6-place Australian Aboriginal consonant system.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] It does not represent any single language, but is instead a simplified form of the consonant inventory of what would be found in many Australian languages, including most Arandic and Yolŋu languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] A typical Australian phonological inventory includes just three vowels, usually /i, u, a/, which may occur in both long and short variants.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In a few cases the [u] has been unrounded to give [i, ɯ, a].
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] There is almost never a voicing contrast; that is, a consonant may sound like a [p] at the beginning of a word, but like a [b] between vowels, and either letter could be (and often is) chosen to represent it.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Australia also stands out as being almost entirely free of fricative consonants, even of the otherwise universal [s].
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In the few cases where fricatives do occur, they developed recently through the lenition (weakening) of stops, and are therefore non-sibilants like [ð] rather than the sibilants like [s] that are common elsewhere in the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Some languages also have three rhotics, typically a flap, a trill, and an approximant (that is, like the combined rhotics of English and Spanish) and many have four laterals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Besides the lack of fricatives, the most striking feature of Australian speech sounds is the large number of places of articulation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Some 10-15% of Australian languages have four places of articulation, with two coronal places of articulation, 40-50% have five places, and 40-45% have six places of articulation, including four coronals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The four-way distinction in the coronal region is commonly accomplished through two variables: the position of the tongue (front, alveolar or dental, or retroflex), and its shape (apical or laminal).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] There are also bilabial, velar and often palatal consonants, but a complete absence of uvular consonants and only a few languages with a glottal stop.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Both stops and nasals occur at all six places, and in many languages laterals occur at all four coronal places.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] A language which displays the full range of stops, nasals and laterals is Kalkatungu, which has labial *p, m*; "dental" *th, nh, lh*; "alveolar" *t, n, l*; "retroflex" *rt, rn, rl*; "palatal" *ty, ny, ly*; and velar *k, ng*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Wangganguru has all this, as well as three rhotics.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Yanyuwa has even more contrasts, with an additional true dorso-palatal series, plus prenasalised consonants at all *seven* places of articulation, in addition to all four laterals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Where vowels are concerned, it has 8 vowels with some morpho-syntactic as well as phonemic length contrasts (i iː, e eː, a aː, ə əː, ɔ ɔː, o oː, ʊ ʊː, u uː), and glides that distinguish between those that are in origin vowels, and those that in origin are consonants.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Kunjen and other neighbouring languages have also developed contrasting aspirated consonants ([pʰ], [t̪ʰ], [tʰ], [cʰ], [kʰ]) not found further south.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Descriptions of the coronal articulations can be inconsistent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The alveolar series *t, n, l* (or *d, n, l*) is straightforward: across the continent, these sounds are alveolar (that is, pronounced by touching the tongue to the ridge just behind the gum line of the upper teeth) and apical (that is, touching that ridge with the tip of the tongue).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] This is very similar to English *t, d, n, l*, though the Australian *t* is not aspirated, even in Kalaw Lagaw Ya, despite its other stops being aspirated.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The other apical series is the retroflex, *rt, rn, rl* (or *rd, rn, rl*).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Here the place is further back in the mouth, in the postalveolar or prepalatal region.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The articulation is actually most commonly subapical; that is, the tongue curls back so that the *underside* of the tip makes contact.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] That is, they are true retroflex consonants.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] It has been suggested that subapical pronunciation is characteristic of more careful speech, while these sounds tend to be apical in rapid speech.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Kalaw Lagaw Ya and many other languages in North Queensland differ from most other Australian languages in not having a retroflexive series.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The first tends to be used in careful enunciation, and the last in more rapid speech, while the tongue-down articulation is less common.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Finally, the palatal series *ty, ny, ly*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] (The stop is often spelled *dj*, *tj*, or *j*.) Here the contact is also laminal, but further back, spanning the alveolar to postalveolar, or the postalveolar to prepalatal regions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The tip of the tongue is typically down behind the lower teeth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] This is similar to the "closed" articulation of Circassian fricatives (see Postalveolar consonant).
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The body of the tongue is raised towards the palate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] This is similar to the "domed" English postalveolar fricative *sh*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Because the tongue is "peeled" from the roof of the mouth from back to front during the release of these stops, there is a fair amount of frication, giving the *ty* something of the impression of the English palato-alveolar affricate *ch* or the Polish alveolo-palatal affricate *ć*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] That is, these consonants are not palatal in the IPA sense of the term, and indeed they contrast with true palatals in Yanyuwa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In Kalaw Lagaw Ya, the palatal consonants are sub-phonemes of the alveolar sibilants /s/ and /z/.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] These descriptions do not apply exactly to all Australian languages, as the notes regarding Kalaw Lagaw Ya demonstrate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] However, they do describe most of them, and are the expected norm against which languages are compared.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Some have suggested that the most appropriate unit to describe the phonotactics of Australian languages is the phonological word.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The optionality of CFIN is cross-linguistically normal, since coda consonants are weak or nonexistent in many languages, as well as in the early stages of language acquisition.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The weakening of CINIT, on the other hand, is very unusual.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] No Australian language has consonant clusters in this position, and those languages with fortis and lenis distinctions do not make such distinctions in this position.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Place of articulation distinctions are also less common in this position, and lenitions and deletions are historically common here.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] While in most languages the word-initial position is prominent, maintaining all a language's contrasts, that is not the case in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Here the prominent position is C1(C2), in the middle of the word.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] C1 is typically the only position allowing all of a language's place of articulation contrasts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Fortis/lenis contrasts can only occur at C1, or at C2 when C1 is a sonorant.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Consonant clusters are often restricted to the C1(C2) position, and are most commonly sonorant + obstruent sequences.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In languages with pre-stopped nasals or laterals, those sounds only occur at C1.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Australian languages typically resist certain connected speech processes which might blur the place of articulation of consonants at C1(C2), such as anticipatory assimilation of place of articulation, which is common around the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In Australia, this type of assimilation seems only to have affected consonants within the apical and laminal categories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] There's little evidence of assimilation between the labial, apical, laminal, and dorsal categories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Many proto-Pama–Nyungan /-np-/ and /-nk-/ clusters have been preserved across Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Heterorganic nasal + stop sequences remain stable even in modern connected speech, which is highly unusual.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The anticipatory assimilation of nasality is quite common in various languages around the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Typically, a vowel will become nasalized before a following nasal consonant.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] However, this process is resisted in Australian languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] There was a historical process in many languages where nasal + stop C1C2 clusters lost the nasal element if CINIT was a nasal.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Also, many languages have morphophonemic alterations whereby initial nasals in suffixes are denasalized if the preceding stem contains a nasal consonant.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] While the existence of phonemic pre-stopped nasals and laterals, contrasting with plain nasals and laterals, has been documented in some Australian languages, nasals and laterals are pre-stopped on a phonetic level in most languages of the continent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] These phenomena are the result of a general resistance to the anticipatory assimilation of nasality and laterality.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] The lack of assimilation makes coda nasals and laterals more acoustically distinct.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Most speakers of Australian languages speak with a 'pressed' voice quality, with the glottal opening narrower than in modal voice, a relatively high frequency of creaky voice, and low airflow.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] This may be due to an avoidance of breathy voice.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] This pressed quality could therefore serve to enhance the clarity of speech and ensure the perception of place of articulation distinctions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Probably every Australian language with speakers remaining has had an orthography developed for it, in each case in the Latin script.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Sounds not found in English are usually represented by digraphs, or more rarely by diacritics, such as underlines, or extra symbols, sometimes borrowed from the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] Some examples are shown in the following table.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In the Northern Territory, 62.5% of Aboriginal Australians spoke an indigenous language at home in 2016.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] In Queensland, almost 95% of Torres Strait Islanders spoke an indigenous language at home in 2016.
[src:australian-aboriginal-languages/australian-aboriginal-languages] A number of linguists and ethnographers have contributed greatly to the sum of knowledge about Australian languages.
